+    // On real libultra, (re-)setting the interrupt mask is a dispatch point: any interrupt pending
+    // during the masked window is serviced, which can wake/switch to a higher-priority thread. The
+    // cooperative ultramodern scheduler otherwise only dispatches inside osRecvMesg/osSendMesg, so a
+    // game-thread busy-wait loop that toggles the int mask (the audio worker's command-dequeue at
+    // state 6) never yields -> starves __scMain -> title state machine frozen at 6. Make osSetIntMask
+    // a cooperative dispatch point for game threads, restoring that semantics. #64.
+    //
+    // MASK-AWARE (W134, #53 -- the hardening tracked in mesgqueue.cpp KNOWN LIMITATION (b)):
+    // real libultra services pending interrupts when the mask is RAISED (re-enabled), never when a
+    // thread LOWERS it (osSetIntMask(OS_IM_NONE)=1 to enter a critical section). Dispatching on the
+    // disable-edge ran other threads inside game critical sections; measured W134: the SFX-player
+    // constructor (func_80076EE4) links its voice handler via alSynAddPlayer and primes the
+    // current-event buffer a few dozen instructions later -- a disable-edge dispatch inside that
+    // window handed the CPU to the audio worker, which dispatched the just-linked handler against
+    // the unprimed (zero) event buffer and SIGSEGV'd in alAudioFrame reading *(player+0x2C)=0.
+    // OS_IM_NONE reaches here as a0 == 1 (the ROM's osSetIntMask(1) critical-section idiom); every
+    // restore passes the saved (enabled) mask != 1, so the audio worker's per-spin restore still
+    // dispatches and the W97 cooperative un-starving is preserved.
+    if (ultramodern::is_game_thread() && (uint32_t)ctx->r4 != 1u) {
